</caption>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,1787,2013]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<taxonomicName authorityName="M. S. Strother" authorityYear="1993" box="[198,426,1788,1813]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costaricensis">
<emphasis box="[198,426,1788,1813]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fidia costaricensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is quite distinctive and is not likely to be confused with any other known species. Males of 
<taxonomicName box="[260,456,1828,1853]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Fidia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="guatemalensis">
<emphasis box="[260,456,1828,1853]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">F. guatemalensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have similar abdominal modifications, but are brassy-black with gold or purple luster, the pronotum is coarsely punctate-reticulate, the elytral disc has coarse, irregular punctate-striae, and the spinose external apical margin of the metatibia is acutely subangulate.
</paragraph>
